entry.content:
"Tap_" is an old terminology from Polymer1 where synthetic "tap" events

where used instead of native "click" events. Even though "tap" events

are no longer used anywhere (crbug.com/812035), occasionally cases of

handlers named with the "Tap_" suffix occur, which will be

automatically flagged from now on.



Most violations revealed by the following command have been fixed in

eiter in precursor CLs or in this CL.

entry.title: Revert "Reduce string conversion cost in style property setters."
entry.content:
This reverts commit 04d9f1126b69ccb4ce93c4b3cc3dd04010687e43.



Reason for revert: Seems to cause WebKit Linux ASAN failure: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/WebKit%20Linux%20ASAN/47967/overview



Original change's description:

> Reduce string conversion cost in style property setters.

>

> When setting x.style.y = z (and we don't hit the special path where z

> is a double), we need to convert z from a v8::String to something that

> we can work with in our C++ parsers. (Unfortunately, it seems we mostly

> cannot just peek into its contents, possibly because it could be moved

> around by garbage collection.) In our existing code, we convert

> implicitly to WTF::String, which causes heap allocation and some hashing.

>

> However, recently CSSTokenizer was changed to support tokenizing

> from StringView instead. In the vast majority of cases, this means

> we don't need to actually heap-allocate anything; we can write out

> the string into a stack buffer and send in a StringView.

>

> linux-perf Pinpoint (95% CI, no PGO):

>

> motionmark_ramp_canvas_arcs [ -1.7%, +0.8%]

> motionmark_ramp_canvas_lines [ -6.0%, +2.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_design [ +0.8%, +5.1%]

> motionmark_ramp_multiply [ +1.7%, +3.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_paths [ +2.2%, +9.2%]

> motionmark_ramp_suits [ +0.4%, +1.6%]

>

> M1 appears to be unchanged, win-10-perf has only small improvements.

entry.content:
This reverts commit 38ddf3f1ce1a26a5d87b70144eebd9bacb8c82d4.



Reason for revert: https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1446426 was found and fixed, hoping that's the cause. Can't repro anymore locally, and CQ run with android-internal-rel and android-internal-dbg run passed.



Original change's description:

> Revert "Reland "Android CCV/CRS: Turn on ChromeRootStoreUsed in fieldtial_testing_config.json""

>

> This reverts commit 212497b77f6a41b5263570aca1ac78b638996537.

>

> Reason for revert: Causing android-arm-tests to fail chrome_test_apk with "EmbeddedTestServer$EmbeddedTestServerFailure: Failed to install root certificate"

>

> Original change's description:

> > Reland "Android CCV/CRS: Turn on ChromeRootStoreUsed in fieldtial_testing_config.json"

> >

> > This reverts commit 3cab5ea4a21787927909463aa527e4ea4ebe0dbd.

> >

> > Reason for revert: Original change broke internal bots when code was run statically on class load; moving back to a ClassHook implementation.

> >

> > Original change's description:

> > > Revert "Android CCV/CRS: Turn on ChromeRootStoreUsed in fieldtial_testing_config.json"

> > >

> > > This reverts commit c55272f6365bb00ba1c260064c66dc6777f094c2.

> > >

> > > Reason for revert: Broke internal bots

> > > https://bugs.chromium.org/p/chromium/issues/detail?id=1442472

> > >

> > > Original change's description:

> > > > Android CCV/CRS: Turn on ChromeRootStoreUsed in fieldtial_testing_config.json

> > > >

> > > > This required modifying tests to ensure that the test root is loaded in X509Utils.java via a ClassHook in ContentJUnit4ClassRunner before the user-added roots are pulled in net/cert/internal/trust_store_android.cc, so that the chrome cert verifier would correctly verify trust for connections to the EmbeddedTestServer. Previous attempts to do this did this at other points in the test loading process, but were unsuccessful for a variety of different reasons, usually in loading the root too late.

> > > >

> > > > We also rely on the fact that the root cert for EmbeddedTestServer is a statically checked in file (at net/data/ssl/certificates/root_ca_cert.pem) as the current solution (starting up the EmbeddedTestServer in a separate APK + calling to get the root cert) requires calling into native code which can't be done easily before the chrome cert verifier loads the user-added roots.

> > > >

> > > > This would be easier if the EmbeddedTestServer was run in process instead of in its own APK; I don't know if it would be feasible or how much work it would be to change this.

entry.title: [Zucchini] Remove misaligned memory access from casted pointers: Part 1/2.
entry.content:
Previously Zucchini copiously accessed memory via:



*reinterpret_cast(*uint8_ptr)



Although this worked for x86 / x64, the code isn't portable, as it can

lead to unaligned memory access on other architectures (e.g., ARM).

Indeed, recent Puffin test failures are caused by this.



This CL mitigates the problem by replacing direct read/write on casted

pointers with explicit memcpy() (amenable to compiler optimization for

fixed size). Note that Zucchini still assumes that it's executing on a

little-endian architecture. Details:



* BufferViewBase (for {Const,Mutable}BufferView):

* read(), write(): Use memcpy().

* modify(): Remove.

* Replace the 2 usages in RelocWriterElf::PutNext with write() using

member field offset.

* Remove test BufferViewTest.Modify.

* BufferSink: PutValue(): Use memcpy().

* BufferSource: {CheckNextValue(), GetValue()}: Use memcpy().

* Add BufferSourceTest.GetValueUnaligned and

BufferSinkTest.PutValueUnaligned.



Indirect read/write from BufferSource.{GetPointer(),GetArray()} will

require more restructuring, and will be handled in a follow-up.

entry.title: Introduce cache_max_size for shared dictionary
entry.content:
This CL introduces a size limitation parameter `cache_max_size_` in

SharedDictionaryManagerInMemory and SharedDictionaryManagerOnDisk.



When `browser.disk_cache_size` profile preference is set, its value is

set to NetworkContextParams.shared_dictionary_cache_max_size by

ProfileNetworkContextService. And it is used by SharedDictionaryManager.

Otherwise, the browser process will calculate appropriate size

using base::SysInfo::AmountOfFreeDiskSpace() (AmountOfPhysicalMemory()

for incognito mode) and propagate it to the network service via

NetworkContext::SetSharedDictionaryCacheMaxSize() IPC message.



We need to calculate the size in the browser process because the network

service process is sandboxed.



The calculation may take some time as it is performed in the background

thread with the BEST_EFFORT TaskPriority. It is possible for the cache

size to exceed the maximum limit, but this is not a significant issue.

The cache eviction logic will automatically delete old dictionaries when

the network service receives the max size.



Not: This CL doesn't implement the eviction logic itself.

entry.title: Build and run build scripts for the Rust stdlib
entry.content:
Now that we can build the build scripts against the prebuilt stdlib that

comes with the compiler, we can use the build scripts that are part of

the stdlib itself when building the stdlib.



This enables optimizations in the stdlib crates depending on the

platform and Rust compiler version like:

- non-aligned memory accesses in compiler_builtins on x86

- SIMD instructions in memchr



A couple crates use `cc::Build` to run a compiler in their build

script which we don't support, so we add a gnrt_config option to

skip those build scripts entirely.

entry.title: Fix waitForDebuggerOnStart bug on auto-attached ServiceWorker Target
entry.content:
When we stop a ServiceWorker and start it again while using selenium,

the ServiceWorker stays in 'starting' state and does not go to

'running'.



This behavior is related to how the Devtools protocol currently

handles waitForDebuggerOnStart flag for auto-attached ServiceWorker

Target.



Currently, ServiceWorkerDevtoolsManager always sets 'pause_on_start'

for the stopped ServiceWorker's agent-host, even if the ServiceWorker

should not pause on start if a Target is attached to the ServiceWorker

(e.g. Target attached with 'waitForDebuggerOnStart:false' option)



This CL adds a conditional check (agent_host->should_pause_on_start())

when setting 'pause_on_start' for a stopped ServiceWorker to avoid

unnecessary pausing.

entry.title: Reduce string conversion cost in style property setters.
entry.content:
When setting x.style.y = z (and we don't hit the special path where z

is a double), we need to convert z from a v8::String to something that

we can work with in our C++ parsers. (Unfortunately, it seems we mostly

cannot just peek into its contents, possibly because it could be moved

around by garbage collection.) In our existing code, we convert

implicitly to WTF::String, which causes heap allocation and some hashing.



However, recently CSSTokenizer was changed to support tokenizing

from StringView instead. In the vast majority of cases, this means

we don't need to actually heap-allocate anything; we can write out

the string into a stack buffer and send in a StringView.

entry.content:
Previously, when the socket returns ENOBUFS (i.e. socket does not have

enough buffer space), we retry writing the packet to the socket

asynchronously. However, before we actually write, the socket can

become closed due to an network idle timeout.



To fix the issue of writing to an invalidated socket, we need to notify

the writer's socket that it has been closed, when the connection is

closed and all the sockets are closed.

entry.title: [iOS] Postpone policy decision callback while app launch pending
entry.content:
As of now, if there is an app launch request pending through `openURL`,

likely because the user is being prompted "Chrome wants to open App",

the web page can still load another page e.g. using `location.href=...`.

This makes it possible for a page to spoof the user by first triggering

an app launch request and then loading a page the user trusts.



To solve this issue, this CL ensures the app launch tab helper keeps

track of any pending app launch request and postpones all later policy

decision callbacks until the app launch completes. If a navigation

request arrives which should trigger an app launch, it will be canceled

if there is already an app launch pending in this tab. App launch

requests are already dismissed if the user is being prompted.



Fixed: 1443722

delegate, which at least makes it clear what's going on, and makes it

hard to accidentally skip the second delegate.
